column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED AS A RESULT OF A PUNCTURE OCCURRING WHEN THE PACKAGE FELL TO THE GROUND.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING DISPOSITION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE CLOSURE AREA.  THE CLOSURE APPARENTLY COULD NOT BE SECURED TIGHT ENOUGH ACCORDING TO THE SPILL CLEANUP AGENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING DISPOSITION.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AS A RESULT OF THE INNER CLOSURE BEING LOOSE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO SEND IT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, THREE TYPE OF PAINT PRODUCTS WERE FOUND: A) ACRYLLIC POLYURETHENE ENAMEL, 1 GALLONS, INNER LABELS SAY"FLAMMABLE", AND C) STANDARD REDUCER, 1 GALLON. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR DID THE SHIPPER COMPLETE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS FORM. MATERIAL 73-84 DEGREES F AND "B" ABOVE HAD A FLASH POINT OF 4 DEGREES F AND "C" ABOVE HAS A FLASH POINT OF 90 DEGREES F. THIS SHIPMENT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY, "PAINT RELATED MATERIAL",3 UN 1263. THE PACKAGE WILL BE HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: I RECEIVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET I PICK UP THE SPILL AND PROCESSED IT THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM WEARING THE PROPER PPE. NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED AT SITE.
AT 19:40 I RESPONDED TO THE SORT AISLE AT 33 DR. WEARING PROPER PPE, I CONTAINERIZED THE HAZARDOUS LEAKER AND BROUGHT IT TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

I RESPONDED TO OB#8 BAY 1010 FOR A SPILL. I USED MY DECISION TREE WHICH LED ME TO MY RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A CLASS 6.1 HAZ-MAT. I CONTAINED AND PROCESSED SPILL THRU THE DMP. NO BALANCE TO RETURN

column62: Over-pressurized; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE ROAD WAS WET AND SNOW COVERED. AFTER THE DRIVER CRESTED THE HILL HE STARTED DOWN THE OTHER SIDE.  ABOUT 400 FT BELOW THE CREST THE DRIVER NOTICED A STATE POLICE CAR PARKED IN THE RIGHT LANE. THE POLICEMAN RESPONDED TO ANOTHER ACCIDENT,  A CAR LOST CONTROL AND LANDED IN A DITCH. THE DRIVER APPLIED THE BRAKES, THE ROAD WAS ICY. THE TRACTOR WAS EQUIPPED WITH ABS, NOT THE CARGO TANKER. THE CARGO TANKER WHEELS LOCKED AND SLID TOWARD THE RIGHT OF THE ROAD. IT HIT THE SHOULDER AND THE TRACTOR & TANKER ROLLED OVER. OUR ER TEAM RESPONDED AND THEY DECIDED TO VENT SOME OF THE PRODUCT TO KEEP THE PRESSURE DOWN BEFORE RIGHTING IT BACK UP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON A PALLET AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A UNKNOWN CAUSE DURING LOADING.  CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, BOOTS, ABSORBENTS, BROOMS AND SHOVELS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE FACILITY FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPING LOCATION IN CHARLESTON, SOUTH CAROLINA.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED BECAUSE OF AN ODOR.  INSIDE THEY FOUND NUMEROUS SMALL BOTTLES OF WHAT APPEARS TO BE SOME TYPE OF FINGERNAIL POLISH.  THERE WERE TWO BOTTLES THAT HAD CRACKED AND SPILLED OUT INSIDE THE BOX.  THE PACKAGE WAS FROM SPAIN SO INFORMATION AS TO THE LIQUID WAS NOT OBTAINED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE HELD PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION.

column168: DRESSED IN FULL PPE I WAS CALLED TO A LEAKER OUTSIDE DOOR #12 IN THE PRIMARY UNLOAD.  I FOUND A PACKAGE WITH A WET SIDE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND LABEL AND A DOT 5-PART LABEL.  I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE FOLLOWING ITS DIRECTION TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  UNDER THE RESPONSE SHEETS GUIDANCE; THE SPILL WAS ISOLATED, THE CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE DISPOSED OF VIA THE DMP PROCESS, THE UNCONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, AND MY PPE WERE DECONTAMINATED.

WEARING MY PROPER PPE, I RESPONDED TO THE RED BELT IRREG TRAY.  THE BOX CONTAINING THE ETHYL ACETATE - I PLACE MY SPILL TUB (THE LIQUID HAD ALREADY ABSORBED TO THE BOX) AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP CAGE TO PROCESS. FOLLOWING MY DECISION TREE AND THE PROPER RESPONSE SHEET - I DMP THE ONE LEAKING BOTTLE AND THE CARDBOARD + ECT. THAT HAD BEEN LEAKED ON.  THE REMAINING 5 BOTTLES OF ETHYL ACETATE WERE NOT LEAKED ON AND OK.  WERE SENT BACK IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  FOLLOWING MY DECONTAMINATED CHECKLIST - I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

I RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PKG IN A TRAILER.  THE HAZ MAT PKG WAS OPEN ON THE BOTTOM.  TAPE FAILED.  BOTTLES FELL OUT &  WERE LEAKING BECAUSE CONTENTS WERE FROZEN.  SINCE CONTENTS WERE FROZEN, PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE BLOATED & LEAKING.  THERE WAS NO PADDING OR PARTITIONS IN THE BOX.  OUTER BOX SHOULD HAVE BEEN TAPED BETTER.

column168: PREVIOUS TERMINAL LOADED SHIPMENT ON TRAILER WITHOUT PROPERLY SECURING CARTON ON PALLET FOR TRANSPORT.  THE CARTON FELL OFF THE PALLET WHEN THE PALLET WAS REMOVED WITH A FORKLIFT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE CARTON FELL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR UPSIDE DOWN WITH THE IMPACT SHATTERING THE PLASTIC TOPS OF THREE OF THE FOUR JUGS INSIDE THE CARTON.  A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF LIQUID ESCAPED FROM THE TREE PLASTIC JUGS. DAMAGED JUGS IN CARTON HELD IN OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  FREIGHT LOADERS SHOULD ALWAYS PROPERLY LOAD HAZ MAT FREIGHT ON TRAILERS TO PREVENT ANY MOVEMENT.

IND DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER IN DOOR 110.  WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING, HE SCRAPED THE BOTTOM OF THE SKID, CAUSED THE RUPTURE IN THE GALLON.  WE LOST ABOUT 1/2 GALLON CORROSIVE MATERIAL, WE PUT OIL DRY IN THE TRAILER, CLEANED OUT AND PUT THE PUNCTURED GALLON IN THE RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED IT IN OS&D.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: AT 19:27CT, STATION LOCATION IN PHILADELPHIA('MUV') CALLED TO REPORT PACKAGE HAD 'EXPLODED' IN BACK OF COURIER VAN. INITIAL CONVERSATION REVEALED PACKAGE FROM TEMPLE UNIV. HOSPITAL, PICKED UP EARLIER IN THE AFTERNOON, HAD EXPLODED IN BACK OF VAN, PACKAGE WAS REPORTED TO HAVE BEEN LABELED FOR DRY ICE AND INFECTIONS SUBSTANCE. ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT SHIPPER OR OTHER HOSPITAL OFFICIALS WERE NOT SUCCESSFUL. VEHICLE IS STANDARD CARGO VAN WITH SEPARATE CAB. LOCAL MANAGEMENT DETERMINED THE VEHICLE COULD BE SAFELY RETURNED TO MUV. THOUGH INFORMATION ON THE SHIPMENT FROM THE SHIPPER WAS STILL LACKING, DOT EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED AT 20:18CT(REPORT#592028@'CREWS)' FAA EASTERN REGION CONTACTED AT 20:29CT(@DEAN)'. CLEANUP OPERATIONS THE FOLLOWING DAY FOUND TRACES OF STAIN IN THE BACK OF THE VAN. HOSPITAL WAS ABLE TO CONFIRM PACKAGE CONTAINED A SINGLE VIAL, WHICH WAS NOT LOCATED, IT IS ASSUMED THE VIAL BROKE DURING THE INITIAL RELEASE OF CARBON DIOXIDE GAS FROM THE PACKAGE THE DRY ICE WAS APPARENTLY SEALED INSIDE OF THE LIQUID/AIR TIGHT SECONDARY CONTAINER. THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 20 OTHER PACKAGES IN THE VAN AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, IN ADDITION TO AN INDENTICAL 6.2 SHIPMENT FROM THE SAME SHIPPER AT TEMPLE UNIV HOSPITAL. ALL PACKAGES WERE GIVEN A DILUTE BLEACH WIPE, THE SECOND 6.2 SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. LOCAL PHILADELPHIA FAA/CAFSO CONTACTED MUV FOR INFORMATION REGARDING INVESTIGATION, STATEMENTS, ETC. THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS HELD AT MUV AT FAA REQUEST.

DISPOSAL  ARRANGEMENTS WILL BE MADE ON MONDAY JANUARY 14, 2002. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WILL PROVIDE WASTE DISPOSAL ACCORDING TO STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE IN THE TERMINAL WAREHOUSE, ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT OPERATED BY AN EMPLOYEE OF OMEGA. APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE CONCRETE FLOOR. THE TERMINAL WAS EVACUATED FOR AN HOUR AND A HALF. THE O'HARE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. O'HARE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING BOOMS, ABSORBENTS, AND SHOVELS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A SIXTY GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM. THE DAMAGE STEEL DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SEPARATE SIXTY GALLON STEEL  OVERPACK DRUM. BOTH OVERPACK DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  FOUR BAX GLOBAL INC. EMPLOYEES (3 BAX GLOBAL EMPLOYEES & ONE OMEGA FLEET SERVICES EMPLOYEE)  WERE EXPOSED AND WERE TREATED BY ON SCENE MEDICAL PERSONNEL. NO FURTHER MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS SOUGHT. ALL FEDERAL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY REPORTING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: CSX TRAIN CREW WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PICKING UP CARS AT NS INTERCHANGE. UPON MAKING "TIE" WITH FMLX17107, PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM MANWAY NOZZLE AREA. MATERIAL IMPACTED GROUND MEDIA COVERING A 10' HALF MOON SHAPE PATTERN. TRAIN CONDUCTOR COWARD WAS LIGHTLY SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT RESULTING IN NON FRA REPORTABLE INJURY. CONSIGNEE FMC RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF SHIPPER DEGUSSA AND FOUND MANWAY BOLTS IMPROPERLY APPLIED. NO EXCEPTIONS FOUND TO GASKET MATERIAL , FLANGIBLE DISC, OR FILTER STONE. THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED, THEN CLOSED WITH BOLTS TIGHTENED IN A CRISS CROSS PATTERN. RAILCAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION ON JANUARY 15TH. CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER GLEASON SCHEDULED TO VISIT WITH SHIPPER REGARDING INCIDENT.

WHILE HANDLING TANK CAR GATX 15927, THE CSXT TRAIN CREW ASSIGNED TO H72315 OBSERVED LIQUID COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR. THE AREA AROUND THE LEAKING CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED. SEVERAL OTHER PARTIES WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO ASSIST INCLUDING THE PRODUCT SHIPPER AND CSXT EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS. THE CXST CONTRACTOR PLACED A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDERNEATH THE LEAK TO HOLD THE RELEASED PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT WAS THEN TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY. APPROXIMATELY 15657 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED IN THIS MANNER. A REMAINING BALANCE OF APPROXIMATELY 10,000 GALLONS WAS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. A PORTION OF THE MATERIAL RELEASED TO THE GROUND WAS RECOVERED BY DIGGING RECOVERY TRENCHES IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE TANK CAR AND RECOVERING THE LIQUID PRODUCT WAS VACUUM TRUCKS. A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF SOIL AND BALLAST WAS EXCAVATED FOR DISPOSAL FROM THE SPILL AREA. UPON CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A CRACK IN THE TANK SHELL. THE CRACK APPEARS TO HAVE ORIGINATED NEAR THE POINT WHERE THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY IS WELDED TO THE TANK SHELL. THE CRACK EXTENDED UP THE RIGHT AND LEFT SIDES OF THE TANK SHELL.

AT 1808 HRS, CSXT TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RECEIVED A REPORT THAT GATX 13500, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (PULP MILL LIQUID) WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MONTGOMERY, AL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER CONTACTED A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AND MAKE REPAIRS. THE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED IN THE MORNING ON 01/26/2002. THEY FOUND THAT FOUR OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LESS THAN HAND TIGHT. THE REMAINING FOUR MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT. THE CONTRACTOR ALSO FOUND THE AIR LINE VALVE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE CONTRACTOR MADE ALL THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND TIGHTENED THE AIR LINE VALVE PLUG. THE CONTRACTOR NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER OF THESE PROBLEMS.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED. THE LID SEAL ON THE DRUM APPARENTLY FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO SHIPPER/RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE AND ODOR WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE UNIT. THE UNIT'S LID SEAL HAD  APPARENTLY FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE LOADING OTHER FREIGHT, ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED AND LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORATED. THE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED.

ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT WHILE UNLOADING, A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SPILLAGE WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER LOADED SHIPMENT ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER FOR EASE OF UNLOADING. HE PLACE A SINGLE LOAD  BAR TO SECURE. PRO#97090884 WEIGHED A TOTAL OF 5,804 LBS. THE DRIVE ALLEGES THAT A CAR CUT IN FRONT OF HIM CAUSING HIM TO STOP SUDDENLY. THE FREIGHT RIPPING THE PLASTIC LINER CONTAINING THE LIQUID. ALL CONTENTS IN THE PORTABLE TANK LEAKED OUT OF THE CONTAINER. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF THE DRIVER WOULD HAVE LOADED THE SHIPMENT IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER & PLACED PLYWOOD DUNNAGE BETWEEN THE PORTABLE TANKS & THE OTHER FREIGHT AND PROPERLY BLOCKED & BRACED THE PORTABLE TANKS AS REQUIRED BY OUR ESTABLISHED FREIGHT HANDLING PROCEDURES  AND THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE D.O.T

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DEFECT ON THE BOTTOM  OF THE DRUM. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH PUTTY AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING FOUR ONE GALLON PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR  OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE RECEPTACLE WAS DAMAGED AND THREE WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY,  ONE HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE BOX AND THE RECEPTACLE BEING PUNCTURE WHILE LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL "C" PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET BOX AND DAMAGED RECEPTACLE WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE THREE UNAFFECTED PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WERE RECOUPED, AND THE RECEPTACLES WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CONTRACTOR PLACED THE LEAKING STEEL DRUM INTO A NINETY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM. ANOTHER STEEL DRUM IN THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SEPARATE NINETY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM. column168: ON 17 JANUARY 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15AM, WHILE JCI - MILFORD WAS DELIVERING 25% CAUSTIC SODA IT WAS DISCOVERED AFTER FLOW OF PRODUCT BEGAN THAT A LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE MANHOLE ASSEMBLY.  THE DRIVER SHUT THE UNLOAD PROCESS DOWN, AND ASSISTED BEAVERDAMS OPERATOR IN DIGGING TRENCH DITCHES TO CONTAIN PRODUCT SPILLED.  THE SPILL WAS HANDLED BY JCI'S RESPONSE TEAM, CAUSTIC NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM METABISULFITE AND VINGAR. THE INVESTIGATION FOUND TANKER 568 MANHOLE ASSEMBLY WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY, FOR A BOLT ON ONE WING NUT WAS NOT FASTENED PROPERLY.

DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT HAD BEGUN TO LEAK FROM AROUND THE INTERNAL VALVE WHILE UNLOADING INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  UNLOADING WAS TERMINATED AT THIS TIME AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER CONTACT WITH THE GROUND.  IT WAS THEN DISCOVERED THAT THE NUTS HOLDING THE INTERNAL VALVE TO THE CARGO TANK WERE NOT FULLY TIGHTENED.  AFTER THEY WERE PROPERLY TORQUED, THE PRODUCT STOPPED LEAKING AND THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED.  SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND WAS CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY CUSTOMER PERSONNEL.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION INTO THE INCIDENT COULD NOT MAKE A DETERMINATION AS TO WHEN OR WHY THE NUTS MAY HAVE WORKED LOOSE.  THERE WAS NO RECORD OF ANY PROBLEMS WITH THE CARGO TANK NOTED DURING LAST INSPECTION.

AFTER PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED INTO CUSTOMER TANK A VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL OF 3-5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  A REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CONDUCT A CLEANUP.

THE SPILLED  MATERIAL  WAS NEUTRALIZED, CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  CORRECTIVE ACTION: THE IBC WILL STAY IN A SECURE POSITION UNTIL THE TRUCK HAS STOPPED.

column168: WHILE EXITING OFF INTERSTATE 26 AT MILE MARKER 172, THE BRIDGE TERMINAL TRANSPORT, INC VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  A WOODEN FRAME INSIDE OF THE TRAILER HAD BROKEN AND CAUSED DAMAGE TO NINE (9) OF THE EIGHTEEN (18) BALES INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF DRY PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. FENN-VAC, INC. OF NORTH CHARLESTON, SOUTH CAROLINA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS REPACKAGED AND RELOADED ONTO A NEW TRAILER SUPPLIED BY BRIDGE TERMINAL TRANSPORT, INC.,  ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  ONE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER OF BROKEN WOOD AND LOOSE PRODUCT WAS TRANSPORTED BY FENN-VAC, INC. TO OAKRIDGE LANDFILL OF DORCHESTER, SOUTH CAROLINA FOR DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  NO FURTHER ACTION IS REQUIRED AT THIS TIME.

A TOW-MOTOR VEHICLE BACKED INTO A 5-GALLON CAN OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE. THE TOP OF THE CAN BURST OPEN SPILLING A COUPLE OF OUNCES OF PRODUCT ON THE LID. C-F PERSONNEL PLACED THE CAN INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SENT IT ON FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

A DRUM OF NAPTHA SOLVENT WAS PUNCTURED DURING OFF LOADING. A FORKLIFT BLADE CREASED THE SEAM ON THE DRUM RELEASING 1.5 GALLONS OF SOLVENT. THE PALLET BROKE WHEN THE FORKLIFT BLADE WAS RAISED. C-F PERSONNEL LAID THE DRUM DOWN TO STOP THE LEAK. THE DRUM WAS THEN PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR DELIVERY.

A CUP OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED FORM A PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING FORM A SEAM IN THE FIBER BOX. ALL PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A OVER PACK AND WILL BE SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. ALL WASTE CREATED WAS PLACED IN A EMPTY PAIL FOR DISPOSAL. DISPOSAL WILL TAKE PLACE WHEN BULK DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENT ARE MADE. IT IS NOT COST EFFECTIVE TO DISPOSE OF A 5 GALLON DRUM WHEN IT CAN BE COMBINED WITH OTHER MATERIALS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WHILE PASSING ANOTHER VEHICLE DRIVER LET VEHICLE WHEELS RUN OFF EDGE OF HARD SURFACE INTO SOFT DIRT AND MUD (NO SHOULDER) CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL RESULTING IN VEHICLE RUNNING INTO MEDIAN STRIP WHERE THE TRAILER WHEELS STRUCK A CONCRETE CULVERT. THIS CAUSED THE TRAILER REAR END TO GO "AIRBORNE" AND WHEN THE TRAILER CAME DOWN THE RIGHT FRONT END STRUCK HARD SURFACE OF THE ONCOMING LANE. THE FRONT COMPARTMENT CONTAINING 3,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE RUPTURED ON CONTACT SPREADING GASOLINE SEVERAL YARDS IN ALL DIRECTIONS. ENTIRE VEHICLE SKIDDED ON THE ASPHALT ROAD SURFACE FOR ABOUT FIFTY FEET. BY THE TIME THE VEHICLE STOPPED SLIDING THE GASOLINE HAD CAUGHT FIRE. THE THREE REMAINING TANKS CAUGHT FIRE AND EXPLODED AT ABOUT FIVE MINUTE INTERVALS. ALL GASOLINE SPILLED FORM THE TANKER BUT IT IS BELIEVED THAT MORE THEN NINETY PER CENT BURNED BEFORE RUNNING INTO THE MEDIAN STRIP AND SHOULDER OF EAST BOUND LANE OF TRAFFIC. NO INDICATION OF GASOLINE RUNNING INTO NAVIGABLE WATER. INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES, A LICENSED HM CLEANUP AND RECOVERY COMPANY, HANDLED CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION. DRIVER HIRING PRACTICES, DRIVER TRAINING, AND ENTIRE SAFETY PROGRAM IS CURRENTLY BEING REVIEWED AND APPROPRIATE ADDITIONAL MEASURES WILL BE PLACED INTO EFFECT AS NEEDED TO ENSURE THERE WILL BE NO ADDITIONAL ACCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE. NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER REFERENCE # 592403

OIL DRIVER WAS REELING IN HIS HOSE AFTER MAKING A OIL DELIVERY AT 103 OVERLOOK TERRACE, LEONIA N.J. INADVERTENTLY THE NOZZLE LEVER HIT THE HOSE ROLLER AS THE DRIVER WAS REWINDING THE HOSE. THIS CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 GALLONS OF # 2 HOME HEATING FUEL OIL TO SPILL ON TO THE SIDE WALK, AND A PATCH OF DIRT BETWEEN THE SIDE WALK AND THE CURB. OIL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND SPEEDY DRY ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE SIDEWALK WAS PRESSURE WASHED.

column168: 2000 STERLING BOBTAIL PROPANE TRUCK STOPPED ON SOUTH BOUND I-75, NEAR EXIT 92 ARABI GEORGIA CRISP COUNTRY. DUE TO ROAD CONSTRUCTION ON ROADWAY. TRAFFIC WAS BACKED UP FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE. A TRACTOR TRAILER (UNITED VAN LINES) CAME UP HEADED SOUTHBOUND AND REAR ENDED A VAN THAT WAS BEHIND THE BOBTAIL WAITING IN TRAFFIC. THE TRACTOR TRAILER PUSHED THE VAN INTO THE BACK OF THE BOBTAIL KILLING TWO OCCUPANTS OF THE VAN. THE PIPING WAS SHEARED OFF THE BOBTAIL WHEN IT WAS STRUCK BY THE VAN. THERE WAS A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PROPANE FIRM THE PIPING. THE TRACTOR-TRAILER CONTINUED PAST THE BOBTAIL ON THE RIGHT SIDE FOR APPROXIMATELY 150 FEET. THE TRACTOR WAS ON FIRE AS IT WENT PAST THE BOBTAIL. THERE WAS ALSO FIRE DAMAGE TO THE VAN THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF THE FIRE ON THE BOBTAIL. THE WIND WAS BLOWING IN A SOUTH - SOUTH WESTERN DIRECTION.

VAN #2 QUICKLY ROTATED CLOCKWISE BEFORE COMING TO REST ON IT'S DRIVER SIDE FACING EAST ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF SOUTHBOUND I-5.  AFTER VEH #2 ROTATED VEH #2T SEPARATED FROM VEH #2 AND ROLLED OVER VEH #1.  VEH #2T ROLLED ONTO IT'S LEFT SIDE CLIMBED ONTO THE GUARD RAIL AND COMPLETED ROTATION TO DRIVE TO REST FACING WEST. BEFORE OUR DRIVER ARRIVED TO UNLOAD, IT HAD RAINED AND THE TANK FLOATED INSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND BROKE THE PLASTIC PIPES ATTACHED TO IT. THE CUSTOMER HAD SOMEONE PUMP THE WATER OUT BUT THEY FAILED TO REPORT THE BROKEN PIPES. OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AND WAS TOLD TO HOOK TO THE PIPE AND PUMP THE LOAD INTO THEIR TANK. OUR DRIVER DID AS HE WAS TOLD BUT COULD NOT SEE THE TANK DUE TO THE HIGH WALL AROUND IT. THE CUSTOMER FOUND THE LEAK AND HAD OUR DRIVER PUMP THE PRODUCT BACK INTO THEIR TANK. NO PRODUCT WAS LOST AND NO PRODUCT LEFT THE CONTAINMENT WALLED AREA. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP RESIDUE.
PAIL WAS PICKED UP AND MOVED TO ANOTHER SKID A WAS SET DOWN TO HARD AND BOTTOM CRACKED. WHAT LEAKED OUT WAS CLEANED UP AND WAITING FOR DISPO FROM CENTRAL OFFICE.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, THE ENTIRE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED DID NOT FIT INTO THE STORAGE TANK RESULTING IN A SPILL. FLOW OF PRODUCT WAS STOPPED AND THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

WHEN THE DRIVER REACHED DELIVERY POINT HE DID NOT NOTICE ANY PRODUCT LEAKING. HE WENT TO CHECK IN WITH THE CONSIGNEE. WHEN HE RETURNED TO HIS VEHICLE HE NOTICED SOME OF THE PRODUCT DRIPPING OUT OF THE OVERFLOW TUBE. HE CHECKED THE CRASH BOX ON TOP OF HIS TRAILER AND HE NOTICED A WET AREA ON ONE SIDE OF THE DOME LID. HE CHECKED ALL THE DOME LID HOLD DOWNS AND HE FOUND ONE THAT NEEDED SOME TIGHTENING.HE SECURED IT.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM AT THE TERMINAL GARAGE.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT HAD RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE FREIGHT FREEZING, AND CRACKING THE DRUM ON THE SIDE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES, ABSORBENTS, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO  A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DAMAGED STEEL DRUM AND SECOND DRUM IN THE SHIPMENT WERE BOTH PLACED INTO EIGHTY GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS,  THE TWO OVERPACKS DRUMS AND ONE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL. FOR DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE ONE GALLON RELEASE OCCURRED INTO CONTAINMENT PADS AT THE RAILYARD.  THE OPERATORS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED THE SPILL MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO BRANCH GENERATED WASTE DRUM. THE OPERATOR WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER RAILCAR BELLY VALVE CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED A PALLET WITH SOME POWDER GRANULES UNDERNEATH IT.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO OF THE BAGS ON A PALLET CONTAINING FORTY BAGS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AND SLIGHTLY RIPPED OPEN AND SLIGHTLY UNINTENTIONALLY RELEASED THEIR CONTENTS.  THIS WAS CAUSED BECAUSE THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE UNDER NEATH THE BAGS ON THE PALLET SUBSEQUENTLY THE WEIGHT OF THE OTHER BAGS PRESSURED THESE TWO BAGS INTO THE NAILS ON THE PALLET WHICH CAUSED THEM TO RIP OPEN.

UPON UNLOADING FREIGHT AT STOP, DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE PAIL HAD BEEN STRUCK BY OTHER FREIGHT IN TRANSIT SUBSEQUENTLY CRACKING BOTTOM OF PAIL CAUSING UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE.  USING ON BOARD SPILL KIT, DRIVER CLEANED UP SPILL WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO DOMICILED FACILITY AS PER INSTRUCTED.  BETTER BLOCKING AND BRACING BY LOADER COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING A PALLET FROM TRAILER WITH FORKLIFT, FORKLIFT OPERATOR STRUCK DRUM WITH FORKBLADES THAT WERE PROTRUDING FROM PALLET HE WAS UNLOADING.  PUNCTURED DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS' SIDE AND REPAIRED WITH PATCH PUTTY.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  THIS UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF FORKLIFT OPERATOR HAD BEEN PAYING ATTENTION TO SURROUNDINGS AND FORKBLADE CLEARANCES.

DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED A BOX LEAKING FROM A PALLET WHILE IT WAS TEMPORARILY BEING STORED AT FACILITY ON DOCK.  BOX WAS REMOVED FROM PALLET AND A ONE GALLON POLY JUG WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE BOX LEAKING.  ALTHOUGH NO ONE WITNESSED OR CONFESSED, IT LOOKED LIKE IT HAD BEEN STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  DAMAGED JUG WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND SPILLED MATERIAL EVAPORATED BEFORE IT COULD BE CLEANED UP.

WHILE STAGING A PALLET ON THE DOCK, FORKLIFT OPERATOR STRUCK DRUM WITH FORKBLADES THAT WERE SLIGHTLY PROTRUDING FROM PALLET HE WAS CARRYING.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE, REPAIRED WITH DRUM PUTTY AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF FORKLIFT OPERATOR HAD PAID ATTENTION TO FORKBLADE CLEARANCES.

column168: A DRIVER WAS REQUESTED TO PULL-OVER AN 18-WHEEL TRAILER TRUCK BY DOT TO INVESTIGATE A SUSPECTED RELEASE IN THE CARGO BED. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR HUNDRED FIFTY POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE,TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET,IN DOLTON,IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM BLOCKING AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DART SAFETY THEN CONTACTED ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL OF NEW JERSEY, WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP. THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP  MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED JUGS WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. A DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC DRIVER WAS PERFORMING A VEHICLE INSPECTION WHEN HE DISCOVERED A SLIGHT DRIP OF A LIQUID NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON DISCOVERY OF THE DRIPPING LIQUID THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED DART'S SAFETY DEPARTMENT, AT WHICH TIME THIS WRITER CONTACTED CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, OHIO. CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP AT THE HUBBARD, OHIO SCENE. ALL MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM, AND THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO PROCEED TO HIS DESTINATION OF CHICAGO, IL.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON STATE ROUTE 59 OUTSIDE OF HOUSTON, TX NEAR A TOWN CALLED HUMBLE. HE  STATED THAT ANOTHER TRUCK WAS TRAVELING IN THE SAME DIRECTION TWO LANES OVER TO HIS LEFT. AS THEY APPROACHED AN UP COMING EXIT THE OTHER TRUCK SUDDENLY SWERVED OVER TO TAKE THE EXIT. MY DRIVER INDICATED THAT THE OTHER TRUCK NEARLY HIT THE FRONT END OF HIS TRUCK SO HE HIT HIS BRAKES TO AVOID A COLLISION. AFTER THIS EVENT MY DRIVER WENT TO THE NEXT EXIT AND WENT TO CHECK HIS LOAD. AS HE STOPPED AT A SAFE LOCATION HE NOTICED A LIQUID STARTING TO COME FROM THE TRAILER, SO QUICKLY CALLED 911 WHO DISPATCHED THE POLICE AND FIRE/HAZMAT CREW TO HANDLE THE INITIAL CLEANUP OF THE INCIDENT. THEN MY DRIVER CALLED CHEMTREC AND REPORTED IT TO THEM. WHEN THIS WAS COMPLETED, HE USED DIRT TO DIKE THE MATERIAL THAT SPILLED ON THE ROADSIDE, UNTIL THE FIRE CREW ARRIVED AND USED CHEMICAL DRY TO STOP THE MATERIAL FROM SPREADING. AT THIS TIME, MY DRIVER CALLED ME AND I TELEPHONED THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE FOR FURTHER ASSISTANCE. I  THAN SPOKE TO THE FIRE CHIEF IN CHARGE AND HE HELPED ME COORDINATE WITH A LOCAL HAZMAT CLEAN UP COMPANY(EAGLE CONSTRUCTION & ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES). THEY HANDLED THE REMOVAL OF THE PUNCTURED DRUM, OVERPACKED THE REMAINING DRUMS, AND THEN WE RETURNED THE LOAD TO THE SHIPPER. THE DRUM THAT WAS PUNCTURED DID SO BY MOVING INTO A CORNER OF A TOTE ALSO ONE BOARD.
THE LOAD TECH WAS MAKING A SPLIT AN WAS CONNECTED TO A FULL RAIL CAR OR FERRIC SULFATE ACID, THAT THE AIR FEED LINE WAS CONNECTED.  THAT PUT PRESSURE INTO THE RAIL CAR THAT'S WHAT CAUSE THE SPILL.
SEE ATTACHED NO ATTACHMENT

column168: A CSXT TRAIN CREW OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR DODX 14242. THE AREA AROUND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CATCH PAN WAS PLACED UNDERNEATH THE LEAK. AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL THE CONTRACTOR FOUND PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE THREADS OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AT A RATE OF ONE DRIP EVERY 2-3 SECONDS. CONTAINMENT WAS PUT UNDER THE VALVE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED. INSPECTION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET SHOWED THAT THE GASKET MATERIAL HAD DETERIORATED AND WAS NOT PROVIDING A PROPER SEAL. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAP AND THREADS WERE CLEANED. ONCE THE NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAP REPLACED THE LEAKAGE STOPPED. AFTER INSPECTING THE CAR FOR ANY FURTHER SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, A CSXT CAR INSPECTOR DETECTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR TANK CAR GATX 93449. THE EMPLOYEE ALSO OBSERVED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD THAT HAD FORMED AROUND THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE AREA AROUND THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED. CSXT CALLED AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR. UPON INSPECTING THE FITTINGS ON THE CAR, THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE LEAK WAS EMINATING FROM THE TANK CAR'S GAUGING DEVICE (SLIP-TUBE TYPE). THE NEEDLE VALVE (SPIT VALVE) ON THE TOP OF THE GAUGE ROD WAS OPEN AND RELEASING PRODUCT. WHEN THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE LEAKAGE STOPPED. INSPECTION OF THE GAUGE ROD NEEDLE VALVE SHOWED THAT THE OUTLET PLUG INSTALLED IN THE VALVE, HAD A WEEPHOLE CUT INTO THE BODY OF THE PLUG. THIS PLUG WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND REPLACED WITH A NEW OUTLET PLUG. ALL FITTING AND VALVES WERE INSPECTED FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: DRIVER LOADED 7,200 GALLONS OF #2 LOW SULFUR DIESEL @ MARATHON ASHLAND, LOUISVILLE, KY, LEFT TERMINAL AND TRAVELED EAST ON KRAMERS LANE.  AS THE UNIT TURNED LEFT ONTO CANE RUN ROAD IT OVERTURNED ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE COMING TO REST ON THE SIDEWALK.  DRIVER EXITED THE TRACTOR THRU DRIVER SIDE WINDOW.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND PLUGGED THE VOIDS AT THE TOP OF THE TRAILER.  NO SPILLAGE HAD OCCURRED AT THAT TIME.  EVIDENTLY THE SEAM/WELDS ON THE 3 BULKHEADS BETWEEN THE COMPARTMENTS FAILED.  PRODUCT FILLED TO BOTTOM VOID DRAIN AND 45 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO ROADWAY.  EMERGENCY PERSONNEL FAILED TO PLUG THE BOTTOM VOID DRAINS AT THE TIME THEY PLUGGED THE TOP VOID DRAINS.  WHILE PRODUCT WAS SPILLING, EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WOULD NOT ALLOW LEWIS PERSONNEL TO PLUG THE DRAIN NOR WOULD EMERGENCY PERSONNEL PLUG THE DRAIN.  THE 45 GALLONS SPILLED OUT OVER A PERIOD OF APPROXIMATELY 15-20 MINUTES.  THERE WOULD HAVE BEEN NO SPILL HAD ALL VOIDS BEEN PLUGGED IMMEDIATELY. * EMERGENCY PERSONNEL DID PLUG THE DRAIN AFTER THE 15-20 MINUTE TIME SPAN HAD ELAPSED.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE BLACK BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. LITMUS TEST READ 10 PH BALANCE RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD ME CAREFULLY APPLY SODIUM BICARBONATE. I RETESTED THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL TO RE-INSURE THAT THE PH BALANCE WAS WITHIN THE RANGE OF BETWEEN 6-9. CLAY ABSORBENT WAS ALSO USE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND AFTERWARDS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE REMAINING 3 PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND AFTERWARDS ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING COULD HAVE PREVENT THE LIQUID SPILL. THE REMAINING 11 PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

SCBA WASN'T USED DUE TO THE LACK OF AN IRRITATING ODOR AND BUILDING VENTILATION. REST OF PARCEL SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION. column168: ACCORDING TO THE REPORTS FROM THE OFFICERS ON THE SCENE AND THE DRIVER, "TONY" (JAUN ANTONIO MORALES) ROLLED THE TRUCK AND TANKER WHILE ATTEMPTING TO COME AROUND A CORNER ON RUCKER CANYON ROAD IN COCHISE COUNTY. TONY STATED THAT HE TURNED UP THE ROAD AND ONCE IT WAS APPARENT TO HIM THAT HE WOULD BE UNABLE TO SAFELY NAVIGATE THE ROAD HE ATTEMPTED TO BACK THE TRACTOR TRAILER TO AN AREA WHERE HE COULD TURN AROUND. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO BACK THE TRAILER DOWN THE ROAD HE REALIZED THAT HE WOULD BE UNABLE TO CONTROL ITS DECENT DUE TO THE ICE AND SNOW ON THE ROADWAY. AT THIS POINT HE ATTEMPTED TO CALL FOR HELP BUT WAS UNABLE TO USE HIS TELEPHONE DUE TO THE LACK OF CELL SERVICE. HE THEN ATTEMPTED TO DRIVE THE RIG OVER THE MOUNTAIN TO A SAFE LOCATION. IT WAS THEN HE ENCOUNTERED THE CURVE IN THE ROADWAY THAT THE TRUCK WAS UNABLE TO SAFELY TRAVEL THROUGH. AS HE MADE THE TURN THE GROUND BENEATH THE REAR AXLE OF THE TRAILER BROKE LOOSE CAUSING THE REAR OF THE TANKER TO SLIDE INTO A DITCH THAT WAS APPROXIMATELY 10' DEEP. THIS SUBSEQUENTLY CAUSED THE TANKER TO TURN OVER ON ITS SIDE AND THUS PULLED THE REAR AXLES OF THE TRACTOR OVER TO APPROXIMATELY 75 DEGREES PERPENDICULAR TO THE ROADWAY. THE LOAD WAS IN ROUTE FROM LORDSBURG, NM TO CADIZ, CA WITH APPROXIMATELY 7,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. OF THE 7,500 GALLONS OF FUEL ON BOARD THE TANKER PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT, APPROXIMATELY 1,500  GALLONS WAS LOST. THE SITE WAS CLEANED BY SOUTHWEST HAZARD CONTROL THROUGH THE USE OF BIOREMEDIATION. NO EXCAVATION WAS NECESSARY AND THE SPILL WAS CONSIDERED RELATIVELY MINOR WITH RESPECT TO THE ORIGINAL REPORTS FROM THE OFFICERS ON THE SCENE. APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS OF THE 6,000 GALLONS REMAINING IN THE TANKER WAS REMOVED BY CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, INC. AT THE SCENE IN AN EFFORT TO REMOVE THE WEIGHT FROM THE REAR AXLE OF THE TRAILER AS IT HAD BEEN DAMAGED IN THE ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER WAS SITED FOR RECKLESS OPERATION OF A VEHICLE, BY-PASSING THE SCALES AND LOG VIOLATIONS AMONG SOME OTHER MINOR THINGS I CAN NOT RECALL. I WAS SITED FOR DAMAGE TO PROPERTY OF THE UNITED STATES AND DAMAGE TO TIMBER AS A RESULT OF A BRIDGE AND A TREE THAT HE ALSO STRUCK DURING THE ORDEAL. I WAS ISSUED THE CITATIONS BECAUSE TONY WAS NO LONGER AT THE SCENE WHEN I ARRIVED. NO PAYMENT WAS NECESSARY FOR THESE REPAIRS AS THE FEDERAL RANGER DECIDED THEY COULD BE REPAIRED BY NORMAL ROAD MAINTENANCE. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON FEDERAL PROPERTY AND WAS THEREFORE UNDER THE JURISDICTION OF THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT. I WAS TOLD TO RELAY TO MY SUPERIORS THAT ALL OF THE VIOLATIONS RECEIVED DURING THE ACCIDENT WERE OF THE LOWEST POSSIBLE STATURE AND THAT NO FELONIES WERE ISSUED AS A RESULT OF TONY'S AND MILBAR'S COMPLETE COOPERATION AND QUICK AND COMPLETE RESPONSE TO THE PROBLEMS ARISING FROM THE ACCIDENT. TONY WAS SAID TO HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY RESPONSIVE TO ALL OF THE QUESTIONS THAT WERE ASKED OF HIM AS WELL AS BEING COURTEOUS AND NOTICEABLY UPSET ABOUT WHAT HAD HAPPENED. BECAUSE OF THIS AND THE FACT THAT THE ACCIDENT WAS OF A NO

CHRIS FROM OLYMPUS TIGHTENED FITTING, CLEANED UP SPILL, AND THIS DRUM, AS WELL AS THE SPILLED MATERIAL IS IN UBI HAZMAT AREA PENDING DISPOSITION. THIS WAS CAUSED BY LOOSE PLUG, FROM SHIPPER.

A PALLET CONTAINING 12 DRUMS HAD 1 DRUM PUNCTURED ON THE BOTTOM BY WHAT LOOKS LIKE A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THIS DAMAGED DRUM WAS IN THE CENTER OF THE PALLET.  THIS PALLET WAS ABOUT 30 FEET INTO THE TRAILER AND AS SOON AS THE HOSTLER OPENED THE DOOR HE COMPLAINED THAT THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  THE CHEMICAL WAS PARTIALLY DRY UPON INSPECTION BUT THE VAPORS WERE OVERWHELMING.  FIRST JEFF TURNER WAS CALLED TO REPORT THE SPILL AND THE HAZMAT CLEAN UP TEAM WAS CALLED.  THE AREA WAS SEALED OFF AND A QUICK FAC DOCK MEETING WAS HELD TO INFORM ALL WORKERS TO STAY CLEAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE FREIGHT FROM THIS TRAILER AND THE FREIGHT FROM ANOTHER, TRAILER DID NOT MAKE IT TO THE FAC WILL BE CAUSE A MINI FAC ON SUNDAY NIGHT.  THIS FREIGHT WAS DAMAGED FROM THE BOTTOM AND THE ONLY KNOWN WAY TO GET KIND OF DAMAGE IS FROM A FORKLIFT BLADE GOING INTO A PALLET AT AN UPWARD ANGLE AND SLIPPING BETWEEN THE RIBS OF THE PALLET.  THERE WERE 10 PICTURES TAKEN WITH A POLAROID CAMERA AND THEY WILL BE ATTACHED TO THE COPIES OF THIS REPORT FOR BOTH JIM LUTZE AND JEFF TURNERS MAIL BOX.  RM CAT HAZMAT TEAM ALSO TOOK APPROX. 10 TO 20 DIGITAL PICTURES AND THEY WILL BE AVAILABLE AS SOON AS THE REPORT AND BILL ARE SENT TO UP/PORTLAND TERMINAL.

THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED A DISTINCT GASOLINE STAIN AND ODOR ON AND COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED TO REVEAL AN AUTOMOBILE ENGINE PART(CARBURETOR). THE UNIT HAD APPARENTLY NOT BEEN COMPLETELY DRAINED OF FUEL PRIOR TO SHIPPING. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT ROY MORALES/FAA/PHX/CASFO ON 01/31/2002 AT 11:30AM(CST).

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TANK CAR, TGAX 131369, LOAD PHOSPHORIC ACID, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHEN IT WAS MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN CINCINNATI,OH. THE ASST. TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT AT CINCINNATI REPORTED THIS CAR WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER RAIL CAR THAT WAS TRAVELING TOO FAST RESULTING A HARD COUPLING WITH THE TGAX 131369. THE RETARDERS USED TO SLOW CARS DOWN DID NOT FUNCTION PROPERLY ALLOWING THE CAR TO ROLL INTO THE TRACK AT A HIGHER THAN NORMAL SPEED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER SENT RESCAR TO INSPECT THE CAR ON 01/26/2002. MS CAROLYN NETTLES, PCS, REPORTED THAT RESCAR FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISK OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE HAD RUPTURED. THEY REPLACED THE DISK AND WASHED OFF THE SIDES OF THE TANK WERE THE PRODUCT HAD SPLASHED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

A CF EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING A PALLET ACROSS DOCK AREA. THE PALLET WAS LOADED WITH CARDBOARD BOXES THAT EACH CONTAINED FOUR 1-GALLON GLASS CONTAINERS OF DICHLOROMETHANE. TWO OF THE BOXES FELL OFF THE PALLET. ONE GLASS CONTAINER BROKE IN ONE BOX AND TWO GLASS CONTAINERS BROKE IN THE OTHER BOX. CF PERSONNEL USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEANUP THE RELEASE ON THE DOCK FLOOR. THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS THEN PLACED ON A PALLET AND WAS PLACED OUTSIDE THE WAREHOUSE. CF PERSONNEL THEN NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. (E.M.I.) OF THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED THAT A RESPONSE TEAM BE DISPATCHED TO THE INCIDENT SITE TO REMOVE THE WASTE AND LAB PACK (E.M.I. JOB#14521) THE REMAINING FIVE 1-GALLON CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL. THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND PLACED THE SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL INTO A 55-GALLON DRUM. THE FIVE 1-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE LAB PACKED INTO A 30-GALLON POLY DRUM. ALL MATERIAL WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE E.M.I. FACILITY WHERE DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS WOULD BE MADE. THE CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT BY THE CF TERMINAL AND E.M.I. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS RELEASE.

column168: CF PERSONNEL DISCOVERED 3 DRUMS THAT WERE LEAKING. AT THIS TIME IT WAS ASSUMED THAT THE DRUMS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT (SODIUM BICHROMATE) HAD BEEN RELEASED. CF PERSONNEL MOVED THE DRUMS TO AN ISOLATED AREA AND NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. (ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE COMPANY) OF THE SITUATION (E.M.I. JOB #14514). E.M.I. DISPATCHED AN ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR TO THE TERMINAL. UPON ARRIVAL THE RESPONSE THEM INSPECTED 8 DRUMS THAT WERE IN THE TRAILER. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BUNGS OF 2 OF THE DRUMS DID NOT HAVE GASKETS. NEW GASKETS WERE INSTALLED AND THE BUNGS WERE SECURED. THE THIRD DRUM HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE ON THE TOP NEAR THE BUNG. IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE PUNCTURE. THIS DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM. THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED THE EXTERIOR OF THE DRUMS AND 1 WOODEN PALLET WAS IMPACTED. THE CONTAMINATED PALLET WAS BROKEN UP AND PLACED IN ANOTHER OPEN TOP DRUM. THE DRUMS WERE THEN PLACED BACK ON A PALLET AND SECURED. 1 DRUM OF WASTE (CONTAMINATED DEBRIS) WAS GENERATED. THIS DRUM WAS SECURED AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS RELEASE. THE ACTUAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WAS LESS THAN 2 GALLONS.

column168: DURING UNLOADING A DEC TRAILER IN DOOR 72, DRIVER (BOB HAYES) HAD 3-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS ON THE SKID. WHILE HE WAS ON LOADING THE FORKLIFT. HEAD GOT RUBBED AGAINST THE DRUM AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THE DRUM. A CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO PREVENT IN THE FUTURE.

REC'D TTL 261419 FROM RKE.  IT WAS A TRUCK LOAD FOR HASSEN CLARK (PRO# 315015525).  6 OTHER BILLS WERE ON THE TAIL AND WHEN THEY WERE LOADED, ONE OF THE NYLON BURLAP SACKS WAS CAUGHT ON THE CORNER & TORN OPEN CAUSING A SLIGHT SPILL OF POWDER.  CHEMTREC & CUSTOMER WERE NOTIFIED.  THE DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AND FREIGHT WAS PROPERLY OVERPACKED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE OR CARDBOARD BETWEEN HAZ MAT & OTHER FREIGHT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: WHEN UPON UNLOADING TRL 281556 ALEX WHITE HAD DISCOVERED THAT THIS SHIPMENT PRO# 335-183-203 - WAS LEAKING DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING & BRACING OF SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS SET BETWEEN 2 SKIDS THAT SLID INTO CARTON'S AND CRUSHED THE CARTON'S CAUSING DAMAGES.

THURSDAY 01/24/02 CWX EMPLOYEE BILL BRAY WAS LOADING HIS TRAILER IN THE 43 WHEN HE CAME ACROSS CWX PRO#491376922 HE THEN PROCEED TO CONTACT THE IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR JON WOOTEN. AFTER ANALYZING THE BOL AND THE FREIGHT, IT WAS DETERMINED THE ORIGIN OF THE LEAK WAS FORM THE CAP. BILL PROCEEDED TO CLEAN THE SPILL, THEN HE TIGHTEN THE FITTING ON THE DRUM FOR SAFE TRANSPORT. FOR FUTURE REFERENCE WHEN DRIVERS ARE PERFORMING PICK - UP AT CUSTOMERS LOCK THEY SHOULD CHECK AND MAKE SURE DRUM FITTINGS AND OR CAPS ARE TIGHTEN SECURELY TO INSURE SAFE TRANSPORT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: GATX 93483 NOTED EMITTING VAPORS BY FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR NANCY HUNTER DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY INSPECTOR HUNTER AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES REVEALED THE "A" END EDUCTION VALVE AND THE VAPOR VALVE WERE IN THE CLOSED POSITION, HOWEVER, THE PLUGS IN BOTH VALVES WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT ALLOWING PRODUCT VAPOR TO ESCAPE. THE PLUGS WERE PROPERLY SECURED STOPPING THE RELEASE. TANK CAR HAS BEEN BAD ORDERED TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT. THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: FILE 2181 F & D, SHIPPER: CN RAIL, AWB YWG 4010789735 MHR.  ON 01/15/2002 AT 00:38 A SPILL WAS REPORTED LEAKING WITH AN ODOR OF GASOLINE IN BUILDING B OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN TOM CASPER AND CECILLA HICKEY DONNED THEIR PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON APPROACHING THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION THEY FOUND THAT IT WAS SATURATED WITH WHAT APPEARED TO BE A PETROLEUM BASED PRODUCT. THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND A PUMP LIKE PART AND UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE PUMP THEY FOUND THAT THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS COMING FROM TWO OPENINGS  AT THE TOP OF THE PUMP UNIT WHICH DID NOT HAVE ANY TYPE OF PLUGS OR CAPS TO PREVENT SUCH LEAKAGE DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS PLACED THE SHIPMENT INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS ADDING ABSORBENT PADS AND FURTHER PLACING THE SHIPMENT INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN TAKEN BY THE SPILL TECHNICIANS AND PLACED  INTO THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THE AREA IN WHICH THE SPILL WAS WELL VENTILATED AND ONCE THE AFFECTED AREA WAS CLEANED THE ODOR OF FUEL DISSIPATED. THE EMPLOYEE WHO FIRST NOTICED THE ODOR WAS ADVISED THAT THE ODOR WAS THAT OF DIESEL FUEL AND THEY RETURNED TO WORK. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED, NO FOLLOW-UP WAS NEEDED. THE IS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 01:13

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: VERN LIBBY, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, REPORTED DAVE FISHER, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, HAD REPORTED A TANKCAR RWTX 021034, HAD SLOSHED PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND DURING A SWITCHING MOVEMENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR WATERWAYS EFFECTED AND THE CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED. SAHM LIBBY REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER HAD ONE BOLT OUT OF PLACE, FIVE OF EIGHT BOLTS FINGER TIGHT, AND TWO OF EIGHT BOLTS LOOSE. ALL BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED. ALSO, THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS RUPTURED AND WAS REPLACED IN KIND. MR.LIBBY, REPORTED ON SCENE WITH HIM WAS DAVE HANSON, CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE AND THEY WERE AWAITING THE ARRIVAL OF A PRESSURIZED WATER SPRAYER TO DECONTAMINATE THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANKCAR. NO STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE REQUIRED.

DENNIS M. JOHNSON, MGR. CTS RESPONDED TO ABOVE RAILCAR THAT WAS REPORTED LEAKING IN A MAIN LINE TRAIN AT BENSON, AZ. UPON ARRIVAL MR JOHNSON OBSERVED TANK CAR BOCX 3011 LEAKING LIQUID ARGON FROM THE CONTROL PANEL ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED A TECHNICIAN TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR. INVESTIGATION BY THE SHIPPER TECHNICIAN AND MR JOHNSON REVEALED THAT THE LIQUID GAUGE LINE HAD BROKEN AT THE COMPRESSION FITTING. REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE FITTING AND CAR ALLOWED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

JACKSON ALSO DISCOVERED THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG, BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND 2 OF 8 MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE/NOT LEAKING. TANKCAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

RAUL HERRERA, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED AND ODOR WAS NOTICED FROM TANKCAR CELX 8349 LOCATED ON RIP TRACK 503 IN THE ENGLEWOOD YARD. RAUL FURTHER STATED NO PERSONEL WERE INJURED AND TANKCAR WAS ISOLATE. CRAIG DENNY, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER DENNY REPORTED THE BOTTOM OUTLET GASKET WAS DETERIORATED. ONCE THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, THE ODOR STOPPED. THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION AND THE CAR DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: KIM KEELING, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR, GATX 36041, HAD A SLOW DRIP AT THE BAILEY YARD IN NORTH PLATTE, NEBRASKA. MR. KEELING DETERMINED THE TANKCAR WAS A RESIDUE EMPTY AND LEAKED LESS THAN A GALLON OF DIESEL FUEL WITH NO CONTAMINATION. MR. KEELING SECURED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM VALVE, AND TIGHTEN THE OUTLET CAP WHICH SECURED THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column168: TANKCAR GATX 55465, REPORTED LEAKING FROM TOP OF CAR. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED, REQUESTED SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC. THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE OVERLOADED/OVER PRESSURED AND VENTING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE CAR WAS SECURED BY MR. JACKSON AND MOVED/ESCORTED TO CHEVRON REFINERY FOR OFFLOADING OF PRODUCT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: VERN LIBBY, SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT II, SEATTLE, WA. WAS NOTIFIED THAT PHIL THOMPSON, RTS, SUPERVISOR, SEATTLE, HAD REPORTED CONTAINER CRXU 462382 WAS LEAKING, CRXU WAS LOADED AS THE TOP CONTAINER IN STACKCAR DTTC 075384 AND WAS LOCATED IN RAMP 5 SEATTLE , WA. LIBBY'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT CONTAINER CRXU 462382 WAS LEAKING AT THE RIGHT REAR THIRD OF THE CONTAINER. PH STRIP TEST OBTAINED A PH READING OF 14 INDICATING AND ACID. CHEMTREC, TOM FLORES WAS CONTACTED AND ASSIGNED CASE #01-11/2202-007 TO THE INCIDENT. FLORES PUT LIBBY IN CONTACT WITH HALDIS FERN, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES, HAZMAT RESPONDER. FERN CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL TO REMEDIATE THE INCIDENT. JASON POTTS, SITE SUPERVISOR, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, HAD BOTH THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND BOTTOM CONTAINER OFF LOADED AND PLACED ON PLASTIC, SEAL 0060502 ZEP MANUFACTURING WAS REMOVED FROM THE RIGHT HASP OF CONTAINER CRXU 462382. THE DOORS WERE OPENED, NOTING IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTING OF PALLET BOARDS AND DOOR GUARD WRAP, WHICH ALLOWED THE LOAD TO SHIFT. SEVERAL PLASTIC CONTAINERS LABELED CORROSIVE WERE SCATTERED THROUGHOUT THE REAR PORTION OF THE CONTAINER, UPSIDE DOWN AND ON THEIR SIDES. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM ONE 275 GALLON WIRE CAGED PLASTIC TOTE LABELED CORROSIVE LIQUID 8, BASIC INORGANIC N.O.S/POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, NOTED WITH FRACTURE IN THE TOP 1/3 OF THE TOTE. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOTE IN QUESTION. THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT IN THE LEAKING TOTE WAS TRANSFERRED TO DOT CERTIFIED TOTE. FURTHER INSPECTION OF CONTAINER CRXU 462382 DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER FLOOR WAS SATURATED WITH PRODUCT, REQUIRING IT TO BE REMOVED AND REPLACED. THEREFORE IT COULD NOT BE RELOADED. THE CONTENTS OF CONTAINER CRXU 462382 WERE TRANSLOADED INTO PATU540512 AND SEAL UPE-489437 APPLIED FOR PROTECTION. CONTAINER CRXU 462382 REMAINS ISOLATED AT SEATTLE PENDING TRANSPORT TO FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL'S SEATTLE FACILITY TO REPAIR THE FLOOR

WHILE CONDUCTING A TANK CAR INSPECTION MCTS ROBERT BAVIER DISCOVERED GATX 81129 WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY. THE BOLTS WERE SECURED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. RMCC WAS ASKED TO MAKE ALL NOTIFICATIONS AND REQUEST A RETURN CALL FROM THE SHIPPER.

TANKCAR UTLX 200159 RELEASED 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OF CAR AT THE ALFALFA YARD, EL PASO. MR. JOHN JACKSON, MR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LEAKING FROM THE VALVE SEAT AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET DEFECTIVE. MR. JACKSON REPLACED THE GASKET, SECURED THE CAR AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. SHIPPER NOTIFIED MR. JACKSON THAT CAR WOULD BE SENT TO SHOP FOR REPAIRS TO LEAKING VALVE SEAT AFTER UNLOADING AT CHEVRON REFINERY.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: RAY SORINO, ENGLEWOOD YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR MTCX 9000, A LOAD OF LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM-LPG, WAS LEAKING. THE TANKCAR IS LOCATED AT THE SETTEGAST YARD ON THE NORTHEAST LEAD. GEOFFREY REEDER, ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED THE SHIPPER BE CONTACTED. UPON ARRIVAL REEDER FOUND FROST ON THE DRAFT GEAR AT THE A END OF TH CAR, INDICATING A LIQUID LEAK. REEDER NOTIFIED THE HOUSTON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM. THE AIR AROUND THE CAR WAS SAMPLED USING A MULTI RAE AND NO FLAMMABLE VAPORS WERE DETECTED. THE HOUSTON HAZMAT TEAM AGREED TO LET THE CAR BE MOVED TO A NEARBY TEAM TRACK FOR TRANSFER. SEAL TEPPCO 3646 WAS REMOVED FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS AND THE VAPORS BURNED THROUGH A FLARE. THE CAR WAS FILLED WITH WATER TO PURGE ANY REMAINING VAPORS. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER AND REPRESENTATIVE OF THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION WERE ON SITE FOR THE OPERATION.

WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ROPER YARD, FOUND TANK CAR GATX98863 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP CONTROL, THE OPERATING ROD WAS MISSING, LEAVING THE CAR OPEN. A PLUG WAS APPLIED TO STOP THE LEAKING CONDITION. RMCC WAS NOTIFIED, THEY IN TURN NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER MR.BILL WEBBER (301-775-8412) WAS UPDATED REGARDING ALL EXCEPTIONS TO THIS CAR.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ROPER YARD, FOUND TANKCAR GATX92866 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY. DISCOVERED THAT 3 OF 8 MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE. MGR RODABOUGH SECURED THE BOLTS AND NOTIFIED RMCC, THEY IN TURN NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER. SHIPPER SINCLAIR OIL MR.BILL WEBBER (307-775-8412) APPRISED REGARDING THE EXCEPTIONS TO THIS CAR.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLACENCE INSPECTIONS IN THE ROPER YARD. OBSERVED TANKCAR GATX52932 WITH FUEL LEAKING AT THE TOP CONTROL. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS INSUFFICIENT PACKING AT THE STEM OF THE OPERATING ROD. THIS ALLOWED FUEL TO LEAK. MGR RODABOUGH TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT. THE CAR, HOWEVER, WILL REQUIRE ADDITIONAL PACKING. RMCC WAS NOTIFIED, THEY IN TURN NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER. SHIPPER, MR BILL WEBBER (307-775-8412) WAS APPRISED OF THE EXCEPTION TO THIS CAR.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: A PALLET BEING UNLOADED FROM TRAILER 0415-9030 WAS NOTED TO HAVE A CARTON OF CORROSIVE/OXIDIZER SOLUTION ON ITS SIDE AND IT WAS WET. CONNIE BURNETT WAS THE DSR IN SPOKANE THAT NOTICED THE CARTON AND HE CALLED ME OUT TO CHECK THE SITUATION. I REMOVED TO CARTON FROM THE PALLET AND PLACED IT UPRIGHT ON SOME CARDBOARD. I OPENED THE CARTON TO SEE WHY IT WAS LEAKING, AND THE CARTONS INSIDE OF THE OUTSIDE CARTON WERE MARKED "THIS END UP-CONTAINS BOTTLE WITH VENT CAP_WILL LEAK IF TIPPED". I BELIEVE THIS CARTON WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE SO THE PALLET WOULD FIT UNDER A LOAD RACK. THE LOADER USED BAD JUDGEMENT IN THIS ACTION. A CHEMICAL OS&D REPORT FILED AND SENT TO SHIPPING, INTERMEDIATE & END SERVICE CENTERS AS WELL AS ALL REGIONAL AND SAFETY SUPERVISORS.

JAMES WILLOUGHBY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR IN DOLORES YARD,2442 EAST CARSON STREET. TANKCAR UTLX 200192 LOCATED IN YARD 41, TRACK 795, DESTINED FOR ASHLAND CHEMICAL COMPANY IN LONG BEACH, CA, WAS NOTED DRIPPING FORM THE BOTTOM NOZZLE BY YARD PERSONNEL. DEAN COOPER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE RESPONDED. DEAN COOPER STATED YARD PERSONNEL MOVED THE TANKCAR TO ASHLAND CHEMICAL COMPANY, 20915 Wilmington AVENUE, CARSON, CA, WHICH IS ACROSS THE ROAD FROM DOLORES YARD. MR. COOPER NOTED METHANOL WAS DRIPPING FROM THE GASKET BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND TANK. MR. COOPER ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE FLANGE, WITHOUT SUCCESS, DUE TO A SUSPECTED BAD GASKET. PRODUCT WAS STILL DRIPPING AT A RATE OF 2-3 DROPS PER MINUTE. THE TANKCAR WAS SPOTTED TO THE DRIP PAN AT ASHLAND CHEMICAL FOR CONTAINMENT AND OFF-LOADING BY ASHLAND PERSONNEL. RMCC MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO CHEMTREC FOR SHIPPER, EQUISTAR, STATE NOTIFICATIONS, AND COURTESY NOTIFICATION TO LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT. SHIPPER TO SHOP THE CAR AND HAVE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALUE INSPECTED UPON RETURN.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings

AGENT WILSON REPORTED HE DISCOVERED A SMALL DRIP COMING FORM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, THE TANKCAR IS A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL. THE TANKCAR WAS ON TRAIN MFWNP 15. AGENT WILSON NOTIFIED KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS. MANAGER KEELING DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT TIGHT. MR. KEELING SECURED THE NUT. MR.KEELING ALSO REMOVED SEAL BUDCO066766 IN THE PROCESS AND HAD TO REPLACE THE SEAL ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET HANDLE WITH UP133510.

DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, TANK CAR GATX 36065 WAS FOUND AROUND THE MANWAY BOLTS. MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE TWO TURNS AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE 3 1/2 TURNS. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, KIM KEELING SECURED THE MANWAY BOLTS AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT.

DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, KIM KEELING FOUND TANK CAR GATX 18585 LEAKING AROUND THE MANWAY. SIX OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WERE FOUND LOOSE. MGR. KEELING TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, TANK CAR GATX 23159 WAS FOUND LEAKING PRODUCT FORM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, KIM KEELING TURNED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE 1 1/2 TURNS TO SECURE. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF A TANK CAR, RESIDUE HYDROCHLORIC ACID, VENTING AT 18TH STREET YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS. MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH ROD BUDIMLIJA WHO ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS VENTING FROM THE TOP AND HE HAD ADVISED ALL PERSONNEL TO STAY AWAY FORM THE CAR. MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TO HANDLE THE RESPONSE AS MR. SEKAVEC WAS IN ST. LOUIS. CONTRACT PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND EVALUATED THE CAR, DETERMINING THE PROBLEM TO BE AN OPEN AIR INLET VALVE THAT WAS ALSO MISSING A CLOSURE PLUG. PERSONNEL CLOSED THE VALVE AND REPLACED THE PLUG, SECURING THE CAR. THEY ALSO NEUTRALIZED THE ACID THAT HAD COLLECTED ON THE CAR AND THEN RELEASED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: ERNIE SIROTEK, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED HE REPAIRED TANKCAR RTMX 21064. THE CAR WAS AT THE OAKLAND YARD. 1400 MIDDLE HARBOR ROAD, AT THE ONE SPOT. IT WAS REPORTED BY A SWITCH CREW THAT PRODUCT WAS SPLASHING OUT OF THE TOP. MR. SIROTEK RESPONDED AND DISCOVERED THE MS-POSITIONED GASKET. HE RE-POSITIONED THE GASKET, RESEALED THE CAR, AND RELEASED IT. THERE WAS NO MORE THEN A GALLON SPILLED, WHICH WAS CONTAINED ON TOP OF THE CAR. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. MR. SIROTEK REQUESTED CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES; OAKLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND CHEM TREC BE NOTIFIED. UPDATE: RMCC CONTACTED GRAY, BNSF SERVICE INTERRUPTION,TO OBTAIN A FAXED COPY OF THE WAYBILL. TANKCAR RTMX 21064 WS BEING INTERCHANGED FORM BNSF AND WAYBILL INFORMATION DID NOT INCLUDE A SHIPPER'S NAME, THEREFORE A CHEM TREC REPORT COULD NOT BE COMPLETED. ONCE OBTAINED NICKI, CHEM TREC, UPDATED REPORT NUMBER 01252002039. NICKI INFORMED RMCC THAT NEITHER THE SHIPPER, GLACIAL GRAIN SPIRITS-BENSON MN,OR THE CONSIGNEE, FLEISCHMANNS VINEGAR CO-OAKLAND CA, WERE REGISTERED WITH THEM. RMCC UPDATED ERNIE SIROTEK, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY. THROUGH TRACING THE CAR AND THE USE OF THE INTERNET A CONTACT NUMBER FOR GLACIAL GRAIN WAS OBTAINED RMCC CONFERRED MR. SIROTEK AND JANET, GLACIAL GRAIN-SHIPPER. MR. SIROTEK INFORMED JANET THE REPAIRS ADMINISTERED TO THE TANKCAR AND THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE WAYBILL NEEDED TO BE CHANGED. JANET CAN BE CONTACTED AT 320-843-4813

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING A TANK CAR INSPECTION MCTS ROBERT BAVIER DISCOVER THE CAR VENTING FORM THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE. THE AREA AROUND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND ALL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE HAD ONE LOOSE SECURING BOLT AND THREE WORN WASHER. THE VENT LINE BLIND FLANGE OF THE RUPTURE DISC HOUSING HAD THREE OF FOUR BOLTS LOOSE WITH ONE MISSING A WASHER. THE WASHER AND MISSING BOLTS WERE REPLACED AND TIGHTENED. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH PIONEER CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVES AND THE CAR WILL BE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED PRIOR TO RELOADING.

WHILE CONDUCTING AN INSPECTION OF TANK CAR SHPX203294, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, ROBERT BAVIER DISCOVERED A LOOSE MANWAY BOLT. THE BOLT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH RMCC AND CHEMTREC. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

TIM POST, ASSISTANT RAMP MANAGER, REPORT INTERMODAL TANK SNTU 400184 WAS REMOVED FROM TRAIN IEWLB 23 AND PLACED ON A INTERMODAL CHASSIS, LOCATED AT SPOT WHITE, CH 549, AT ICTF YARD, 2401 EAST SEPULVEDA BOULEVARD, BECAUSE IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK.  THE LEAK WAS BELIEVED TO BE COMING FROM THE TUBES IN THE TOP SPILLWAY BOX AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK. THE LEAK AS CONTAINED ON THE CHASSIS AND NO PRODUCT HAD REACHED THE GROUND. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER REPORTED THE TANK WAS LEAKING FROM THE BLIND FLANGE ON THE LIQUID LINE AT THE TOP  OF THE TANK. RMCC MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO CHEMTREC FOR SHIPPER CONTACT, CAL OES, AND CITY OF LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPARTMENT. JOE CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE ADVISED THAT NEITHER EVERGREEN AMERICA, SHIPPER, NOR EVERGREEN'S CUSTOMER, M.G. MAHER, THE FREIGHT FORWARDER, WERE MEMBERS OF CHEMTREC. JOE STATE STOLT COMPANY, HOUSTON, TX, OWNER OF THE TANK, WAS A MEMBER OF CHEMTREC AND WOULD BE NOTIFIED. MANAGER COOPER CONFERRED WITH BILL, OPERATIONS MANAGER FOR STOLT COMPANY, AND ADVISED HIM THAT DON HODDER, UNIROYAL COMPANY, WAS NOTIFIED AS UNIROYAL LEASED THE TANK FROM STOLT. STOLT WAS ADVISED THE LEAK CONSISTED OF A CUP OF FREE LIQUID STANDING ABOVE THE WAFER VALVE ON THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE, AND THAT THE FOUR BOLT FLANGE WAS LOOSE AS WELL. LESS THAN A PINT OF MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE INSIDE OF THE SPILL BOX DECONTAMINATED. THE FLANGE WAS SECURED TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL RELEASE. AS IT APPEARED THE VALVE WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BY PASS, STOLT AGREED THE VALVE NEEDED TO BE REPLACED. THE IM TANK WAS MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE CUSTOM'S DOCK AND SECURED FOR THE NIGHT. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, STOLT WANTED TO MOVE THE IM TANK TO VENTURA LESBRO, A CONTRACTED IM TANK REPAIR FACILITY. WHILE REINSPECTING THE TANK, THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHEN THE TANK WAS MOVED. column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT LOCATION AT APPROXIMATELY 8:45 AM. TANKS WERE GAUGED TO ENSURE PRODUCT WOULD FIT INTO STORAGE TANKS. AS REGULAR PRODUCT WAS FLOWING INTO STORAGE TANKS, THE REGULAR TANK SPILL BUCKET FILLED WITH PRODUCT. DRIVER SHUT OFF PRODUCT FLOW FOR WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS THE REGULAR PRODUCT. HOWEVER THE PRODUCT HE SHUT THE FLOW OFF FOR WAS MID-GRADE. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO DRAIN THE SPILL BUCKET BY OPENING THE DRAIN WITHIN THE BUCKET HOWEVER, THE CHAIN WAS BROKEN ON THE DRAIN. THE DRIVER THEN TRIED TO USE A SCREW DRIVE TO OPEN THE DRAIN, HOWEVER THE DRAIN WOULD NOT STAY OPEN. DRIVER TRIED TO USE FILL PIPE INSTEAD OF DRAIN. IN ORDER TO GET THE PRODUCT TO DRAIN OUT OF THE SPILL BUCKET THROUGH THE FILL PIPE, THE DRIVER PULLED FITTING OFF OF FILL PIPE. HOWEVER, PRODUCT WAS STILL FLOWING. APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS SPILLED. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT ALL INTERNAL VALVES TO TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO USE HIS EMERGENCY SPILL KIT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED SOON AFTER. THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN A TWO-DAY SUSPENSION WITHOUT PAY FOR THE INCIDENT AND COUNSELED ON THE CORRECT UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: MARIE LLIMALEOTA (ORDER PROSTATE SEEDS OF AMERICA) LEFT A MESSAGE AT 0730 ON THE MBI CELL PHONE REQUESTING INFORMATION ABOUT HOW SOON WE COULD DELTA DASH A PACKAGE TO PALISADES HOSPITAL.  ROBYN STUMP RETURNED HER CALL AT 0800.  MARIE STATED THAT THE PALISADES ORDER #079436 WAS NEVER RECEIVED BY THE HOSPITAL.  FEDEX WAS CONTACTED AT 0815 TO TRACK THE PACKAGE.  THE TRACKING NUMBER FOR THE PACKAGE IS 802125725530.  THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM MBI ON FRIDAY, JANUARY 11, 2002, FOR DELIVERY ON MONDAY, JANUARY 14, 2002.  FROM THE DETAILED TRACKING INFORMATION AVAILABLE ON-LINE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED BY THE SORTING FACILITY IN MEMPHIS SUNDAY, JANUARY 13, 2002.  A FEDEX REPRESENTATIVE STATED THAT THEY WERE DILIGENTLY LOOKING FOR THE PACKAGE AND HAD MARKED THE INCIDENT AS A MEDICAL EMERGENCY.  SHE WOULD CALL AS SOON AS ANYTHING WAS KNOWN ABOUT THE PACKAGE. AT 1607 WE RECEIVED A FACSIMILE LETTER FROM KEITH L. NEELY IN THE CUSTOMER RELATIONS DEPARTMENT AT FEDEX INDICATING THAT FEDEX WAS STILL LOOKING BUT WAS UNABLE TO LOCATE THE SHIPMENT.  I CONTACTED MR. NEELY AT 1635 BY PHONE (901-922-1616) TO IDENTIFY THE PACKAGE AS RADIOACTIVE MEDICAL DEVICE AND EMPHASIZE THE IMPORTANCE OF FINDING AND RETURNING THE PACKAGE TO MBI.  AT 1651 A MR. GOULD WAS CONTACTED AT NRC OPERATIONS BY PHONE (301-951-0550) TO REPORT THE MISSING PACKAGE AND TO RECEIVE GUIDANCE AS TO MY COURSE OF ACTION.  MR. GOULD RECOMMENDED THE DEQ BE NOTIFIED AND MS. PAM BISHOP WAS CONTACTED BY PHONE (405-702-5164) AT 1654.  OVER THE NEXT EIGHT DAYS CALLS WERE PLACED TO NUMEROUS FEDEX OFFICES INCLUDING SANTA FE BRANCH, AIRPORT OFFICE AND DANGEROUS GOODS OFFICE FOR WESTERN UNITED STATES.  THREE MEETINGS WERE HELD AT MBI WITH FEDEX OFFICIALS INCLUDING THE DANGEROUS GOODS DIRECTOR FOR WESTERN UNITED STATES.  JANUARY 25, 2002  I CONTACTED DR. PARKER, FEDEX RSO IN MEMPHIS, AT 0956 TO ASCERTAIN THE STATUS OF THE SEARCH FOR THE MISSING SHIPMENT.  DR. PARKER INDICATED THE PROBABILITY WAS SMALL THAT THE SHIPMENT WOULD EVER BE FOUND AND SHOULD IT TURN UP I WOULD BE CONTACTED BUT THE SEARCH WAS "WINDING DOWN".  DR. PARKER FURTHER INDICATED THAT THE TENNESSEE DEQ WAS "CLOSING THE FILE" ON THE SHIPMENT. BASED UPON THIS INFORMATION THE SHIPMENT SHOULD BE CLASSIFIED AS LOST UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE.  AFTER CAREFUL REVIEW OF THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS, OUR PROCESSES, AND THE EVENT, I FEEL WE COULD NOT HAVE AVOIDED AND ANY CHANGES WE MIGHT MAKE WOULD HAVE NO IMPACT ON PREVENTING THIS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ARRIVE AT TERMINAL 08:45  PRE-TRIP POWER UNIT 456 387.  08:50 ATTACH TRAILERS 7003/7004 TO 456 389.  DID WALK AROUND, CHECKING, SUSPENSION AND GAUGES NOTICED 2% GAUGE WAS REGISTERING 2090.  FINISH UP PRE-TRIPPING UNIT AT 09:15  10:30 DROVE TO SEIU LAKE AND PARKED AT THE PROPANE LOADING TERMINAL.  ATTACH LOADING HOSE, ATTACH GROUND CABLE.  SET WHEEL CHECKS. OPEN ALL VALVES AND SET UP LOAD METER WITH LOAD TICKET.  PROCEEDED WITH LOAD.  % GAUGE STILL SITTING AT 20%.  WHILE LOADING TRAILER, WALKED UP THE HILL TO CHECK LEVEL IN BULLETS  AND WHAT BULLET I WAS DRAWING PRODUCT FROM, THERE WAS ENOUGH PRODUCT IN THE BULLET FOR THE LEAD.  WENT BACK TO LOADING DOCK TO BEGIN PAPER WORK.  AFTER PERIOD OF TIME THE PUMP QUIT LOADING AT 33,350 LT.  PUMP WOULD RESTART AND OPERATOR WAS CALLED TO TROUBLE SHOOT CAUSE; WE DECIDED TO MOVE LOAD HOSE TO PUP AND PROCEED TO LOAD SAME.  AT THIS TIME LEAD WAS READING 20%.  NOT KNOWING THERE WAS PRODUCT LEFT IN TRAILER FROM PREVIOUS DELIVERY I LEFT THE 33,350 LTR AS IT WAS.  CHECK AIR SUSPENSION GAUGE AND IT WAS READING 43 LBS.  FINISH LOADING PUP AND STOPPED PUMPING  AT 26,650 SO THAT I WAS NOT OVER GROSS.  DISCONNECTED HOSE, GROUND CABLE REMOVE CHOCK BLOCKS LEAD WAS STILL AT 20%.  13:30 DROVE TO VAUX HAUL BOUGHT A COTTAGE DID A WALK AROUND CHECK AND GAUGE MOVED TO 50% DID NOT SEE ANYTHING UNUSUAL AND PROCEED TO SHELBY MT.  CROSSED COUTTS SCALE WITH NO PROBLEM AND PROCEEDED TO CUSTOMS CONTROL BOOTH.  15:00 WHILE STOPPED AT CONTROL BOOTH AGENT IN CHARGE NOTICED GAS VENTING AT THE TOP OF TRAILER 7003.  HE TOLD ME TO PARK ON SCALE AND GO TO BROKER AS GAS HAD NOT BEEN REGISTERED.  GAS WAS STILL VENTING AT THIS TIME.  WENT BACK TO CUSTOMS FROM BROKER WITH MY PAPERS AND WAS TOLD TO MOVE TRUCK TO AN AREA SOUTH OF BUILDINGS NEXT TO FENCE AND TOLD BACK TO BACK TO THE OFFICE AND TO STAY AWAY FROM UNIT.  AGENTS DECIDED TO CALL BEN TAYLOR TO TAKE EXCESSIVE PRODUCT FROM TRAILER AS THE GAUGE NOW WORKING READS 100%.  BEN TAYLOR WAS GOING TO BE 1 1/2 FROM ARRIVING BUT IN THE MEAN TIME REIMER BULK HAD TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT NEAR BY AND HE CAME TO TAKE EXCESS FROM TRAILER.  UPON ARRIVAL WE PROCEED TO HOOK UP WITH HOSES FOR TRANSFER OF PRODUCT. CUSTOMS HAD STOPPED ALL TRAFFIC IN AREA, POLICE FIRE OFFICIALS WERE CALLED OUT. OFF LOAD LEAD 7000 TO 78%  AS REQUESTED BY OFFICIALS.  ALLOWED TO LEAVE 02/01/21 TO GO TO SHELBY TO UNLOAD ALL PRODUCT.  02/01/22.

PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN TIMOTHY HINES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON HIS ARRIVAL HE FOUND 1 FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. HE REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN 2X 240 ML GLASS BOTTLES OF "TRICHLOROACETIC ACID, 8, UN 1839, PG II". THESE BOTTLES HAD SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE. ONE OF THESE BOTTLES HAD BROKEN, LEAKING ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS. HE PLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO DECLARE THE CONTENTS AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. SECTION 41,42,43,44,45 A THE CARGO TANK DID NOT FAIL OR CAUSE DAMAGE UPON OUR INVESTIGATION. 42B & 43B THE LOOSE FITTING CAUSED THE SPILLAGE.
